normalized": false, "mention": "neurons", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.4719339907169342, "span": {"begin": 670, "end": 677}}], "text": "Glutamate (Glu) release into the synaptic cleft is primarily caused by excitatory glutamatergic neurons, however there is evidence showing astrocytes releasing glutamate through a calcium-dependent process (Nedergaard et al., 2002). A mechanism explaining how astrocytes release glutamate is not well defined, but it could be released through exocytosis (Nedergaard et al., 2002). When focal seizures start, the firing of glutamatergic neurons releases glutamate (Lallement et al., 1991). While the change in spiking activity of individual neurons at seizure onset appears to be heterogenous, there is an apparent increase in neuronal firing rate in some populations of neurons (Truccolo et al., 2011).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 15:15:28 +0000 2026"}